[[Image:Loebs NY Deli, Washington DC.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Loeb's NY Deli</center>]] [[File:Loebs deli washington dc.jpg|thumb|right|The menu board and counter in the deli]] '''Loeb's NY Deli''' is a historic [[Kosher style|kosher-style]] [[Delicatessen|deli]] in [[Downtown, Washington, D.C.|downtown]] [[Washington, D.C.]], United States.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/02/AR2010070205335.html "After 51 years, Loeb's deli will leave 15th Street for new home"], July 3, 2010 by Jonathan O'Connell, ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref> Opened in 1959 by Walter Loeb, the deli was originally located at the corner of 15th and G Streets, NW, in a space currently occupied by the [[Old Ebbitt Grill]]. In the 1970s the deli moved to the [[Lafayette Building (Washington, D.C.)|U.S. Export-Import Bank]] (Lafayette) building, and was made to move again in 2010 because of a [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|Recovery Act]]-funded renovation.<ref>[http://www.weeklystandard.com/articles/what-happened-loeb-s-deli_552971.html "What Happened to Loeb’s Deli?"] By Ike Brannon Mar 14, 2011, Vol. 16, No. 25, ''[[The Weekly Standard]]''</ref> It is now located at 1712 I Street, and run by Dave, Marlene and Steve Loeb, the children of founder Walter Loeb.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/going-out-guide/wp/2016/04/22/three-matzoh-ball-soups-we-cant-stop-kvelling-about/ Going Out Guide - Three matzoh ball soups we can’t stop kvelling about] ''Washington Post'' By Gabe Hiatt; April 22, 2016</ref>
